---
description: Global project standards for Next.js + Prisma + shadcn + RHF + Zod + Zustand
alwaysApply: true
---

You are working in a modern Next.js App Router codebase.

Core architecture rules:
- Prefer React Server Components by default
- Prefer Server Actions for mutations and form submissions
- Only use client components when browser APIs, interactivity, or client state are required
- Do not introduce unnecessary API routes for internal app-to-db flows
- Prefer direct Prisma usage on the server
- Prefer route handlers only for webhooks, external integrations, or public HTTP endpoints

Code quality rules:
- Use TypeScript everywhere
- Keep functions and components small and focused
- Prefer explicit typing for exported APIs
- Avoid any
- Avoid large files and duplicated logic
- Reuse existing utilities and patterns before inventing new abstractions
- Keep naming clear and business-oriented

Project structure rules:
- Put shared server utilities in src/lib
- Put server actions in src/actions or near the relevant feature when already colocated
- Put validation schemas in src/lib/validations or feature-local schema files
- Put reusable UI in src/components
- Keep feature-specific code grouped by feature when practical

When making changes:
- First inspect nearby files and follow existing conventions
- Make the smallest correct change that fits the architecture
- Do not rewrite unrelated code
- Preserve existing behavior unless the task explicitly requires a change